```

Exercise: Responsive Card Layout

Let's combine several of these concepts into a practical exercise:

```html
<div class="card-container">
  <div class="card">
    <h2 class="card__title">Card 1</h2>
    <p class="card__content">This is some content for card 1.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <h2 class="card__title">Card 2</h2>
    <p class="card__content">This is some content for card 2.</p>
  </div>
  <!-- Add more cards as needed -->
</div>
```

```scss
:root {
  --primary-color: #3498db;
  --secondary-color: #2ecc71;
  --text-color: #333;
  --card-padding: 20px;
}

.card-container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
  gap: 20px;
  padding: 20px;
}

.card {
  background-color: white;
  border-radius: 8px;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  overflow: hidden;
  transition: transform 0.3s ease;

  &:hover {
    transform: translateY(-5px);
  }

  &__title {
    background-color: var(--primary-color);
    color: white;
    margin: 0;
    padding: var(--card-padding);
  }

  &__content {
    color: var(--text-color);
    padding: var(--card-padding);
  }
}

@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  .card-container {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}
```

This exercise demonstrates the use of CSS Grid for layout, CSS variables, BEM methodology, transitions, and media queries for responsiveness.

These advanced CSS concepts will significantly enhance your ability to create sophisticated, responsive, and visually appealing web applications. As you work on your infinite canvas project, these techniques will be invaluable for creating a polished user interface and ensuring a great user experience across different devices.
